\begin_inset space \hspace*{\fill}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
t-Copula degrees of freedom: 25.25
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The degrees of freedom signifies the extent of the fat tails.
 A degree of freedom of infinite is essentially a normal distribution; previous
 literature have found t-copulas with a degree of freedom of 32 to be a
 very close approximation of a normal copula.
\change_inserted 0 1271604506

\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\paragraph_spacing double
Methodology
\change_inserted 0 1271603780
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Methodology"

\end_inset


\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Arithmetic and 
\change_deleted 0 1271605921
Compounding
\change_inserted 0 1271605922
Geometric
\change_unchanged
 Returns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
We use two methods for calculating returns for a given time period.
 In the arithmetic approach, returns from a period are added to returns
 in the next period.
 In the 
\change_deleted 0 1271605940
compounding
\change_inserted 0 1271605941
geometric returns
\change_unchanged
 approach, returns from a period are multiplied to the returns in the next
 period.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

 be the return during period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}$
\end_inset

 be the portfolio value at the end of period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, we can express the two approaches as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\text{Geometric: }V_{t+1}=V_{t}\cdot(1+r_{t+1})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\text{Arithmetic: }V_{t+1}=V_{t}+r_{r+1}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The use of arithmetic returns is mathematically and computationally convenient.
 Our initial analyses utilize arithmetic returns before extending the mean-CVaR
 framework to consider 
\change_deleted 0 1271605930
compounding
\change_inserted 0 1271605932
geometric returns
\change_unchanged
 and rebalancing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Conditional Value at Risk (CVaR) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
In order to calculate the CVaR of a certain portfolio over a set of simulations,
 we sort the average returns of all the simulations from lowest to highest
 and take the average of the lowest 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
beta * Number of Simulation$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\beta\text{-CVaR}=\frac{{1}}{(\beta\cdot n)}\sum_{i=1}^{\beta\cdot n}R_{i}\label{eq:CVaR calculation}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$n$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the number of simulations, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the i-th lowest simulated return of 
\change_deleted 0 1271626543
an asset class
\change_inserted 0 1271626562
the portfolio for a given set of weights
\change_unchanged
, and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
beta$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the desired CVaR level (expressed as a percentage, e.g.
 5%).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Analytical Mean-Variance Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double

\change_deleted 0 1271632954
 
\change_unchanged
The 
\change_deleted 0 1271646896
Markowitz (1952)
\change_inserted 0 1271646901

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "markowitz"

\end_inset


\change_unchanged
 framework analytically calculates the optimal set of portfolio returns
 and variances using the historical average return and historical standard
 deviation of each asset class along with the historical covariance between
 each pair of asset classes.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be the fixed portfolio monthly return rate
\change_inserted 0 1271626464
,
\change_deleted 0 1271626654
 and 
\change_inserted 0 1271626655

\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}$
\end_inset


\change_unchanged
 
\change_inserted 0 1271626629
be 
\change_unchanged
the average historical monthly return of 
\change_deleted 0 1271626664
each
\change_unchanged
 asset class
\change_inserted 0 1271626676
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 be the number of asset classes (seven)
\change_unchanged
.
 The optimization problem
\change_inserted 0 1271626643
 for one level of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\change_unchanged
 can be expressed as follows:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\min_{w_{1},w_{2},...w_{n}}\text{{\sigma^{2}}}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{a})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\change_inserted 0 1271626472

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double

\change_inserted 0 1271625869
where
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sigma^{2}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{a})=\sum_{i=1}^{a}w_{i}^{2}\cdot\sigma_{i}^{2}+2\sum_{i=1}^{a}\sum_{j>i}^{a}w_{i}\cdot w_{j}\cdot\text{Cov(}i,j\text{) }\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\text{Cov(}i,j\text{)}=\sigma_{i}\cdot\sigma_{j}\cdot\rho_{ij}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\change_inserted 0 1271625743

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double

\change_inserted 0 1271625871
subject to
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
