\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Optimal Mean-CVaR Efficient Frontiers 
\change_deleted 0 1271621359
Graphed 
\change_unchanged
in the Mean-Variance Framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
We took the weights from the resulting optimal efficient frontiers from
 the mean-CVaR framework for single period arithmetic, single period 
\change_inserted 0 1271606747
geometric
\change_deleted 0 1271606747
compounding
\change_unchanged
, and multiple period rebalancing and graphed them in the mean-variance
 framework.
 We did this to compare how much the optimal mean-CVaR portfolios sacrifice
 in variance in order to achieve lower downside losses.
 
\change_inserted 0 1271606976
The resulting efficient frontiers are shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:meanvariance_Corresponding"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
Our results indicate that the optimal mean-CVaR portfolios for all three
 
\change_deleted 0 1271621767
anlyses
\change_inserted 0 1271621767
analyses
\change_unchanged
 have slightly higher variances than the optimal mean-variance efficient
 frontier (< 0.3%).
 Although there is a slightly higher variance in the optimal mean-CVaR portfolio
s in comparison to the optimal mean-variance portfolios, the optimal mean-CVaR
 portfolios have much less downside risk as CVaR (0.3 - 1.0%).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
This suggests that the cost of protecting against downside risk is only
 slightly higher variance in the portfolio's returns.
 This supports our hypothesis that the mean-CVaR framework, both for single
 period and rebalancing, outperforms the mean-variance portfolio and can
 be a powerful tool 
\change_deleted 0 1271607011
for investors and academics 
\change_unchanged
to better understand downside risk.
 
\end_layout

